    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nI'm writing a Lua plugin for nvim - it connects to **v:servername** (i.e. to itself) to get **ui-event-grid_line**/**ui-event-hl_attr_define** events for its needs. I had the attempt to make it a few years ago, but I was stuck on #31726.\n\nNow I'm creating a **uv.new_pipe()** to communicate with nvim server via msgpack messages, and everything works fine, I have a working prototype (it sends **nvim_set_client_info()** + **nvim_ui_attach()**, then reads events until the flush comes out, works as expected to work).\n\nBut my problem is that I can't use **vim.mpack** module (right now I'm using 3rd party msgpack module) - because when I'm receiving a chunk from the pipe it can contain multiple messages (also last one can be partial) and **vim.mpack.decode** works with data than represents a complete single message. **msgpackparse()** is also not an option - it can retrieve multiple message from the string but also breaks on partial message at the end of the string.\n\nUsing any 3rd party library is painful, at least because of msgpack extensions. Nvim is using these at least for buffer and window IDs (I definitely saw it in the **win_viewport** event which I'm planning to use), maybe somewhere else. Even if library supports extension there is no documentation (at least I didn't find it) on msgpack extension types which nvim is using. I would like to use vim.mpack for my needs If possible (also vim.mpack.decode makes handy *nil -> vim.NIL* replacement).\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n```lua\n---@param data string\n---@param offset? integer -- Message's first byte position (1 by default)\n---@return any? -- The parsed message (or nil if message was partial)\nfunction vim.mpack.decode_one(data, offset) end\n```\n\nThis signature is similar to [this](https://github.com/kieselsteini/msgpack#msgpackdecode_onebinary_data-position).\n\nP.S. I know there are (were?) plans for Lua-side RPC clients (#31868) but It's still not there.",
