        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I just found out than **vim.mpack** also has the **Unpacker** table (not documented, found [here](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/master/src/mpack/lmpack.c#L1143)) and it works like a charm for me:\n\n```lua\npipe:read_start(function(read_err, chunk)\n  assert(not read_err and chunk)\n  \n  recd_data = recd_data .. chunk\n  local start_pos = 1\n\n  ---@type fun(data: string, start_pos: integer?): any?, integer?\n  local unpacker = vim.mpack.Unpacker()\n\n  while start_pos <= #recd_data do\n    -- Don't know now stable this API is but it's working\n    local ok, msg, new_start_pos =\n      pcall(unpacker, recd_data, start_pos)\n    if not ok or msg == nil then\n      if start_pos > 1 then\n        recd_data = recd_data:sub(start_pos)\n      end\n      return\n    end\n\n    assert(type(new_start_pos) == \"number\")\n    start_pos = new_start_pos\n\n    handle_msg(msg)\n\n  end\n\nend\n```\n\nMaybe it's easier to document this **vim.mpack.Unpacker** object rather than change existing functions?\n\nP.S. None of existing functions work with extension types (**msgpackparse()** replace any extension type with vim.NIL IIUC, both **vim.mpack.Unpacker** and **vim.mpack.decode** returns underlying extension bytearray as a string, can't even get the extension ID), but looks like it's not that much of a problem for me. I inspected ext type 1 using for window IDs (the one I'm planning to use) - its data is just packed int16 string so it's easy to parse.\n\nP.P.S. Looks like it's a low priority task so if **vim.mpack.Unpacker** is stable enough for using I can close this issue.",
